## 1. One-Line Summary

- The Hook — Xiom Jekyll & Hyde C52.5 is a high-performance, sticky hybrid powerhouse that bridges the gap between traditional Chinese tackiness and European ESN tension.
- Archetype — Aggressive Power-Looper / Modern Hybrid Attacker.

## 2. Performance Analysis

- Speed & Gears
    - Passive Block Speed: Relatively slow and muted. The sticky topsheet and hard sponge absorb energy, preventing the ball from flying long, but requiring you to actively push the ball over the net.
    - Active Loop Speed: Extremely high. Once you penetrate the 52.5-degree sponge with a full bodily swing, it unleashes a massive amount of kinetic energy.
    - Linearity vs. Trampoline: Highly linear. You get exactly what you put in. The trampoline effect is almost nonexistent on touch shots, only activating on high-impact drives.
    - Mid-Distance Carry: Excellent, provided you have the physical strength to sustain the power. The sponge has immense bottom-out resistance.

- Spin Generation
    - Top-End Spin: Elite level. It rivals Dignics 09C and boosted Hurricane 3 when brushing the ball with full power.
    - Opening Loop: Extremely secure. The sticky topsheet bites into heavy backspin effortlessly, allowing for slow, ultra-spinny opening loops.
    - Serve Quality: Fantastic. The tackiness allows you to generate massive backspin or sidespin with minimal wrist snap, keeping serves incredibly short and low.

- Control & Short Game
    - Touch Play: Superb. The hard 52.5-degree sponge combined with a sticky topsheet acts like a brake for pushes and drop shots, making it very easy to keep the ball short.
    - Spin Sensitivity: High. Because the topsheet grips the ball so well, it also grips incoming spin. You must read spin correctly and adjust your racket angle.
    - Flick Window: Generous for the banana flick (Chiquita) due to the grip, but traditional flat flicks require precise timing to avoid the ball dragging down into the net.

- Throw Angle (Arc)
    - Trajectory: Medium-high.
    - Arc Behavior: The ball arcs up quickly over the net and dips viciously upon hitting the opponent's side of the table, causing it to kick forward aggressively.

- Spin-Interaction Behavior
    - Against Heavy Topspin: Phenomenal. It does not get overwhelmed by incoming spin. You can grip over the top of incoming loops with ease.
    - Against Heavy Backspin: Highly forgiving if you brush, but punishes flat hits. The tackiness lifts backspin almost automatically if your stroke is correct.
    - Error Pattern: Most errors will be netting the ball due to a lack of active effort on passive shots, or missing long when misreading heavy topspin.

## 3. Technique-by-Technique Breakdown

- Serve
    - Easily one of the rubber's strongest attributes. Generates massive bite.

- Receive
    - Push/Stop: Deadly accurate. The ball simply drops dead off the racket if you want it to.
    - Flick: Forehand flat flicks require a very open angle; brush-flicks work much better.
    - Chiquita/Banana: Excellent. The topsheet catches the ball beautifully, allowing for heavy topspin receives over the table.

- Loop/Drive
    - First Loop (3rd Ball): Highly dependable against underspin, giving massive rotation.
    - Continuous Looping: Requires excellent footwork and stamina. The rubber does not help you if you are out of position.
    - Power Loop / Kill: Devastating. The 52.5 sponge provides immense structural support for killer blows.

- Countering
    - Counter-Topspin: Top-tier. You can counter loop right off the bounce with immense confidence.
    - Punch Counter / Active Block: Good, but requires a very firm wrist and active forward motion.

- Blocking
    - Passive Block: Can feel a bit "dead." The ball might drop into the net if you just hold your bat there.
    - Active Block: Very stable. Adding a slight forward press utilizes the sponge tension effectively.

- Smash & Flat Hit
    - Mediocre. The tackiness slows down flat impacts, and the hard sponge makes flat smashes feel a bit blunt. It prefers topspin over flat hits.

- Defense
    - Chop: Surprisingly viable for occasional chopping due to the extreme grip and dead touch on slow impacts.
    - Lob: Safe and incredibly spinny, making it hard for opponents to smash decisively.

